{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492405"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:28:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1050"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1050"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.19,0.06,0.22,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53583"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39038"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6104"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6113"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53583"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 56-year-old man of Turkish origins presents to his General Practitioner after an episode of left iliac fossa pain. This pain came on gradually and lasted about 12 hours before resolving spontaneously. The physical examination is unremarkable. On the basis of a presumed diagnosis of diverticulitis, the GP arranges a CT scan. A full blood count and serum biochemistry come back normal. The CT scan does not show any evidence of diverticulitis and the only abnormality found is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and no further action","Hydatid serology","Endoscopic ultrasound","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA gallstone is visible in the gallbladder and this is almost certainly an incidental finding and has nothing to do with the patient\u0027s presentation (Image). In reality, all this patient needs is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance\u003C/strong\u003E - on the assumption that his pain was not gallstone-related. If the CT suggested evidence of potential complications of gallstone disease (eg thickening of the gallbladder wall and cholecystitis), then further follow-up would be required. Most gallstones never cause any symptoms and can be left well alone. If biliary symptoms do occur, then the patient might be advised to have the gallstones treated (cholecystectomy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid serology \u003C/strong\u003Emight be warranted if there was a lesion visible in the liver. The liver looks completely normal on this CT image. Hydatid disease is caused by the larvae of a flat tapeworm E Granulosus. This patient does come from a part of the world where hydatid disease is endemic. Hydatid disease used to be seen frequently in the sheep farming regions of Australia, but with better hygiene and other strategies, the disease is no longer prevalent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Eis often used as an investigative tool to evaluate malignancies (gastric, pancreatic) and to assess potential biliary problems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EERCP \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be both diagnostic and therapeutic for biliary pathologies such as ascending cholangitis, symptomatic choledocholithiasis and even gall stone pancreatitis. In such cases, ERCP might be warranted if the patient presents with cholangitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMCRP \u003C/strong\u003Eis used increasingly as a non-invasive tool to visualise the whole of biliary tree. This is usually done for suspected choledocholithiasis, biliary strictures (both benign and malignant), chronic pancreatitis and pancreatic cystic lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are no clinical indications that this patient requires any further imaging related to his biliary system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic gallstones in gall bladder does not require immediate attention unless symptomatic"],"references":["Bortoff GA, Chen MY, Ott DJ, Wolfman NT, Routh WD. Gallbladder stones: imaging and intervention. Radiographics. 2000 May;20(3):751-66. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10835126/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39038"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1050"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15887"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20414"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15887","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15887"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/23df324b-661f-4fe0-a9d1-2f41e705cb8e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/23df324b-661f-4fe0-a9d1-2f41e705cb8e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":764,"height":595}},{"type":"media","id":"20414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20414"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dwTWrwnqWc6dkHPDSNIbMUJFNXJhGg.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dwTWrwnqWc6dkHPDSNIbMUJFNXJhGg.jpg"